## Commercial recommendation: renew for four months at twice the previous rate

The proposed rate adjustment is based on the change in responsibility, risk and expected output. The continuation covers more than feature coding:

- institution-wide solution architecture and data ownership design;
- ERP, Google, communications and payment-provider integration;
- student, staff, campus, finance and learning access controls;
- migration, reconciliation, failure recovery and auditability;
- production security, monitoring, backup and support readiness;
- cross-department requirements, vendor coordination and acceptance testing;
- staff training, controlled rollout and post-launch stabilisation; and
- protection and maintenance of the working website, admissions and LMS capabilities during major integration work.

A two-times contract rate is therefore recommended as a scope-adjusted continuation fee, not merely a time extension of the original LMS contract. Third-party subscriptions, SMS charges, Google Workspace licensing, ERP vendor fees, payment-provider charges and infrastructure costs should be budgeted separately by Airads.

**Requested approval:** continue the current technical ownership for four months under a revised contract at twice the previous rate, with the deliverables in this report forming the basis of the statement of work and acceptance review.

## Completion should be measured by operational acceptance

The continuation should be considered successful when:

1. authorised users can enter the correct Campus Operations or LMS workspace using one governed identity;
2. agreed student, staff, programme, campus, enrolment and fee data synchronises with the ERP and exceptions are visible;
3. self-paced, live-online, streamed and blended learning journeys operate with reliable progress and attendance evidence;
4. Google Classroom and selected live-class providers pass a controlled production pilot;
5. admissions, payment, class and reminder notifications are delivered through approved email and SMS providers with logs and retries;
6. management reporting reconciles website, ERP, payment and LMS information;
7. sensitive administration is server-controlled, role-based and auditable;
8. backup, monitoring, incident handling and recovery procedures are documented and tested; and
9. staff and pilot users complete acceptance testing before phased rollout across campuses.
